name: typescript-style
description: TypeScript style and type-safety rules for writing idiomatic, maintainable TS code. Covers type annotations, imports, naming, enums, error handling, discriminated unions, readonly, optional properties, and more. Load this skill when writing, reviewing, or refactoring TypeScript code to enforce consistent conventions.
---

# typescript-style

Enforce consistent TypeScript conventions when writing, reviewing, or refactoring TS code. These rules apply to ALL TypeScript work unless the project explicitly overrides them.

## When to use

- Writing new TypeScript code
- Reviewing TS code for style/type-safety issues
- Refactoring existing TS files
- User asks to "follow TS best practices" or "clean up types"

## Rules

All rules below are mandatory unless explicitly overridden by the project's own style guide.

---

### 1. No default exports

Use named exports. Default exports create ambiguity at the import site.

```ts
// BAD
export default function myFunction() {}

// GOOD
export function myFunction() {}
```

Exception: frameworks that require it (e.g. Next.js pages).

---

### 2. Use `import type` for type-only imports

Prefer top-level `import type` over inline `import { type ... }`.

```ts
// BAD
import { type User } from "./user";

// GOOD
import type { User } from "./user";
```

Inline `import { type ... }` may not be erased by all transpilers, leaving a side-effectful import behind.

---

### 3. No new enums

Don't introduce new enums. Use `as const` objects instead. Retain existing enums.

```ts
const Size = {
  xs: "EXTRA_SMALL",
  sm: "SMALL",
  md: "MEDIUM",
} as const;

type SizeKey = keyof typeof Size;        // "xs" | "sm" | "md"
type SizeValue = (typeof Size)[SizeKey]; // "EXTRA_SMALL" | "SMALL" | "MEDIUM"
```

Numeric enums produce a reverse mapping, doubling `Object.keys()` count — another reason to avoid them.

---

### 4. Prefer `interface extends` over `&` intersections

The `&` operator has poor TS compiler performance. Use `interface extends` for inheritance.

```ts
// BAD
type C = A & B;

// GOOD
interface C extends A, B {}
```

Use `&` only where `interface extends` is impossible (e.g. mapped types, conditional types).

---

### 5. Discriminated unions

Proactively model data with multiple shapes as discriminated unions. Prevents the "bag of optionals" problem.

```ts
// BAD — allows impossible states
type FetchingState<TData> = {
  status: "idle" | "loading" | "success" | "error";
  data?: TData;
  error?: Error;
};

// GOOD — impossible states are unrepresentable
type FetchingState<TData> =
  | { status: "idle" }
  | { status: "loading" }
  | { status: "success"; data: TData }
  | { status: "error"; error: Error };
```

Use `switch` on the discriminant to handle variants.

---

### 6. `readonly` by default

Mark object type properties `readonly` by default. Omit only when mutation is intentional.

```ts
type User = {
  readonly id: string;
  readonly email: string;
};
```

---

### 7. Optional properties — use sparingly

Only use `?` when the property is truly optional. When omission would be a bug, use `T | undefined` instead — forces the caller to explicitly pass it.

```ts
// BAD — easy to forget
type AuthOptions = {
  userId?: string;
};

// GOOD — caller must explicitly pass undefined
type AuthOptions = {
  userId: string | undefined;
};
```

---

### 8. Declare return types on top-level functions

Annotate return types on module-level function declarations. Helps tooling and other AI assistants.

```ts
const myFunc = (): string => {
  return "hello";
};
```

Exception: JSX components — return type is always JSX, no annotation needed.

---

### 9. Naming conventions

| thing | convention | example |
|---|---|---|
| files | kebab-case | `my-component.ts` |
| variables, functions | camelCase | `myVariable`, `myFunction()` |
| classes, types, interfaces | PascalCase | `MyClass`, `MyInterface` |
| constants, enum values | ALL_CAPS | `MAX_COUNT`, `Color.RED` |
| gene
